    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Refers to collars and ruffs that were made of Venetian lace or a similar lace; they were an article of fashionable dress in 18th-century Europe and European colonies. They typically include deep, acute-angled points of lacework. The term refers to the appearance of such collars in portraits by the famous painter, Anthony van Dyck (also spelled "van Dyke").</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000078859/Collins English Dictionary [online] (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000092017/Picken, Dictionary of Costume and Fashion (1987)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Verwijst naar kragen en fraises van Venetiaans kant of een vergelijkbare soort kant; ze waren in de 18de eeuw een modeartikel in Europa en de Europese koloniën. Ze worden gekenmerkt door kantwerk met diep ingesneden, scherpe punten. De term verwijst naar het uiterlijk van dergelijke kragen in portretten van de beroemde schilder Antoon van Dyck (soms gespeld 'Van Dycke').</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指稱以威尼斯蕾絲或類似的蕾絲風格製成的衣領及輪狀皺領；在西元十八世紀間的歐洲與歐洲殖民地中，這類物品被公認為是相當時髦的裝扮。這種領子通常有著複雜尖銳的鋸齒狀蕾絲。此詞彙指稱由著名畫家安東尼．凡戴克（Anthony van Dyck，亦拼為van Dyke）的肖像畫中所採用的這類衣領樣式。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Bezieht sich auf einen Kragen oder eine Halskrause, die aus venezianischer oder ähnlicher Spitzer hergestellt wurde; er war Teil modischer Kleidung im 18. Jahrhundert in Europa und den europäischen Kolonien. Er hatte üblicherweise breite, spitzwinkelige Enden aus Spitze. Der Begriff bezieht sich auf das Auftreten solcher Kragen in Portraits des berühmten Malers, Anthony van Dyck (auch "van Dyke").</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
